6}], "full_text": "Radiology\nCardiac Imaging Modalities\nThe selection of an imaging modality depends on the clinical requirement for spatial\nresolution, functional data, or tissue viability.\nPlain X-Ray When we image the heart, we check:\nThe Posteroanterior (PA) view is the -Position -Size, borders and chamber enlargement\n-Calcifications\nstandard for cardiac X-ray. It is performed\nat a distance of 150 cm with the beam Others:\ndirected from the back (posterior) of -Aortic shadow -Pulmonary trunk -Pulmonary vascularity\n-Other lung anomalies -Rib cage\nthe patient while they hold the cassette.\nClinical Assessment Criteria:\n• Position: Normally, the cardiac apex is on the left.\n• Size: Measured via the Cardiothoracic Ratio (Maximum horizontal cardiac width /\nMaximum horizontal thoracic width).\n◦ Normal: <50% in adults.\n◦ Children: Up to 60% is considered normal.\n• Gross enlargement of the heart:\n-Pericardial effusion -Multivalvular disease -Cardiomyopathy -Ischaemia\n-Epstein anomaly -Atrial septal defect -Pulmonary stenosis -Myxoedema.\nEchocardiography (ECHO)\nUtilizing grey scale and Color Doppler, ECHO is the most\ncommon modality for examining cardiac disease.\n• Capabilities: Assesses\n-anatomy -structure -valvular pathology -blood flow\n-tumors -thrombi -cardiac contractility/function.\n• Limitations:\n◦ Operator-dependent results.\n◦ \"Acoustic window\" issues caused by obesity or burns.\n◦ Difficulty imaging hidden areas like the cardiac apex and right ventricle.\n82"}